function findBall(grid) {
    const m = grid.length;
    const n = grid[0].length;
    const result = new Array(n).fill(-1);

    for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        let x = 0, y = i;

        while (x < m) {
            let nx = x + 1;
            let ny = y + grid[x][y];
            if (ny < 0 || ny >= n || grid[x][ny] !== grid[x][y]) break;
            x = nx;
            y = ny;
        }

        if (x === m) {
            result[i] = y;
        }
    }

    return result;
}
```


    1. Initialize the result array with a size of n and fill it with -1.
2. Loop through the columns of the grid.
3. For each ball dropped from the i-th column, store the current position (x, y) as 0, i.
4. In each step, calculate the next position of the ball based on the direction provided by the grid cell (i.e., x + 1, y + grid[x][y]).
5. Check if the ball would hit a wall or get stuck in a "V" shaped pattern: if the next y-coordinate is out of range or the direction in the next cell is different.
6. If neither condition is fulfilled, update the current position to the next position.
7. When the ball reaches the bottom (x == m), update the result[i] with the final y-coordinate.
8. Return the result array.

